1
00:02:50,700 --> 00:02:51,496
Roberte

2
00:02:52,540 --> 00:02:53,336
Roberte!

3
00:02:53,900 --> 00:02:55,697
Leave me alone.

4
00:03:35,660 --> 00:03:38,572
- Close the window.
It’s cold.

5
00:03:45,220 --> 00:03:48,576
- You can't miss the
first migration of the year.

6
00:03:48,780 --> 00:03:50,133
Go by yourself.

7
00:03:50,340 --> 00:03:53,491
- A flock of ducks
before the equinox, that's rare.

8
00:03:53,700 --> 00:03:58,455
- Oh, the equinox! For 40 years,
it’s all you ever think about.

9
00:03:58,660 --> 00:04:01,891
- But it's you who wanted to
go hunting this morning.

10
00:04:02,100 --> 00:04:04,330
I don't want to anymore.

11
00:05:12,020 --> 00:05:13,248
How much is that?

12
00:05:13,460 --> 00:05:14,779
3 shots

13
00:05:15,380 --> 00:05:16,813
That’s not 3 shots.

14
00:05:17,020 --> 00:05:19,614
-3, I swear.
Look again.

15
00:05:34,340 --> 00:05:36,535
I’ll go downstairs
to prepare the rifles.

16
00:05:38,980 --> 00:05:40,254
Hurry up.

17
00:05:45,460 --> 00:05:47,018
Horrible Milan

18
00:06:06,860 --> 00:06:10,455
I can't see a thing. Why
did you wake me so early?

19
00:07:14,420 --> 00:07:16,854
- Don’t move.
Look.

20
00:07:43,060 --> 00:07:44,413
I love that.

21
00:07:45,020 --> 00:07:47,580
It’s like a girl undressing.

22
00:07:48,780 --> 00:07:50,338
Milan!

23
00:08:13,860 --> 00:08:14,656
It’s beautiful.

24
00:08:14,860 --> 00:08:17,374
- Yes. Very beautiful.
It’s a jay.

25
00:08:20,180 --> 00:08:21,977
But that’s not game.

26
00:08:22,180 --> 00:08:23,374
It is. People eat them.

27
00:08:26,140 --> 00:08:27,334
You aimed well.

28
00:08:27,540 --> 00:08:29,417
It was flying quite high.

29
00:08:29,620 --> 00:08:30,973
You’re a good shot.

30
00:08:32,180 --> 00:08:33,454
It’s the male.

31
00:08:34,300 --> 00:08:36,256
The female must be worried.

32
00:08:38,180 --> 00:08:39,249
Look!

33
00:08:45,260 --> 00:08:47,820
We can shoot it from
under the trees.

34
00:09:00,580 --> 00:09:01,490
Hey!

35
00:09:01,700 --> 00:09:02,735
No.

36
00:09:24,660 --> 00:09:28,448
We should’ve shot the female.
It would’ve been more humane.

37
00:09:32,100 --> 00:09:35,536
- It's true, I’m like a woman
from those realist songs.

38
00:09:35,740 --> 00:09:37,139
Yes. A drunk!

39
00:09:37,340 --> 00:09:42,289
One day I’ll find you, sitting on the
sidewalk with two litres of red wine.

40
00:09:42,500 --> 00:09:44,536
That’s how I’ll end up.

41
00:09:56,180 --> 00:09:56,930
What is it?

42
00:09:57,140 --> 00:09:58,459
Do you see that tree?

43
00:09:58,660 --> 00:09:59,531
Yeah, why?

44
00:09:59,540 --> 00:10:02,612
- The pigeons settle in it.
- Oh let me go!

45
00:10:06,220 --> 00:10:09,769
- They sleep on the
large branches.

46
00:10:09,980 --> 00:10:12,335
You have to shoot
almost straight up.

47
00:10:55,220 --> 00:10:57,370
The pigeons are in your dreams.

48
00:11:16,180 --> 00:11:17,499
You told me...

49
00:11:18,860 --> 00:11:21,738
You told me:
"I found a new love,..

50
00:11:21,940 --> 00:11:24,295
".. and I’m leaving you. "

51
00:11:24,940 --> 00:11:29,536
I begged you to stay,
but you left anyway.

52
00:11:30,220 --> 00:11:31,335
I hate you.

53
00:11:32,820 --> 00:11:33,935
Of course.

54
00:11:35,020 --> 00:11:37,773
Me, for years
I dreamed..

55
00:11:37,980 --> 00:11:40,619
.. I entered
a night club,..

56
00:11:40,820 --> 00:11:42,970
.. and I found you there
with a man,..

57
00:11:43,780 --> 00:11:47,090
.. and you told me:
"This is my new lover.

58
00:11:47,380 --> 00:11:49,974
And you left
with him, laughing.

59
00:11:52,780 --> 00:11:54,896
- Do you still have
that dream?

60
00:11:55,100 --> 00:11:55,976
No.

61
00:11:56,180 --> 00:11:56,930
Of course.

62
00:11:57,860 --> 00:11:58,690
Hey!

63
00:12:03,620 --> 00:12:04,655
Shit!

64
00:12:06,700 --> 00:12:09,339
- There! You have
to know what you’re doing.

65
00:12:09,540 --> 00:12:13,533
If you hunt ducks,
you can’t shoot pigeons.

66
00:12:13,740 --> 00:12:17,938
-4 shots won’t wake every
duck in the neighbourhood.

67
00:12:18,140 --> 00:12:21,496
- You can’t hunt with
a woman who isn’t serious.

68
00:12:21,700 --> 00:12:25,613
You always end up
embarrassing me.

69
00:12:42,300 --> 00:12:43,813
That pigeon was fast.

70
00:12:44,020 --> 00:12:45,294
Of course it was.

71
00:12:45,500 --> 00:12:49,129
- They call them "rowers"
because they row..

72
00:12:49,340 --> 00:12:53,618
.. with their large wings,
silently like champions.

73
00:12:54,540 --> 00:12:56,770
Ducks can’t row.

74
00:12:58,060 --> 00:13:01,336
They make noise
like amateurs.

75
00:13:01,540 --> 00:13:04,976
The pigeon passed by
like a ghost ship

76
00:13:07,340 --> 00:13:08,455
I adore you.

77
00:13:09,020 --> 00:13:09,975
Me too.

78
00:13:53,580 --> 00:13:58,256
What a country! You can’t hunt
in a country if there’s no game.

79
00:13:58,460 --> 00:14:00,576
It isn't duck season yet.

80
00:14:00,780 --> 00:14:03,897
- so what, they shoot hares
on opening day.

81
00:14:04,100 --> 00:14:06,739
This winter, we’ll go to the river.

82
00:14:06,940 --> 00:14:10,410
We'll make such a massacre
that you will be disgusted

83
00:14:10,620 --> 00:14:14,056
and with wild geese,
the most beautiful game.

84
00:14:14,260 --> 00:14:15,613
Sure. Say,..

85
00:14:17,660 --> 00:14:20,254
.. why don’t we go
to the casino tonight?

86
00:14:20,900 --> 00:14:21,810
No.

87
00:14:22,020 --> 00:14:26,172
- We should! I’m better
at roulette than at hunting.

88
00:14:26,380 --> 00:14:30,259
- We’d lose what we spend
here in a month.

89
00:14:30,460 --> 00:14:33,020
- We can leave a month early.
- No.

90
00:14:33,820 --> 00:14:35,253
You’re a bastard.

91
00:14:35,940 --> 00:14:37,089
Of course.

92
00:14:37,620 --> 00:14:39,212
But it’s true!

93
00:15:02,140 --> 00:15:04,051
You’re overacting!

94
00:15:10,420 --> 00:15:11,933
Ah! You brought it along.

95
00:15:12,140 --> 00:15:13,573
I’ve done well, haven’t I?

96
00:15:17,980 --> 00:15:20,255
- You've had a drink, huh?
Sitting by yourself just now.

97
00:15:20,460 --> 00:15:21,688
Just 2 swigs.

98
00:15:29,780 --> 00:15:31,008
Shall we go on?

99
00:15:31,500 --> 00:15:33,172
I’m tired.

100
00:16:10,340 --> 00:16:12,296
She’s a bold one.

101
00:16:12,500 --> 00:16:14,775
She has a tender look.

102
00:16:14,980 --> 00:16:17,813
Well that doesn't mean anything.

103
00:16:52,980 --> 00:16:55,699
- Hello, Madame Milan.
- Hello, Radiguette.

104
00:16:56,060 --> 00:16:57,539
Hello.

105
00:16:57,740 --> 00:16:58,695
So?

106
00:16:59,260 --> 00:17:01,649
- Oh, nothing.
A thrush and a jay.

107
00:17:01,860 --> 00:17:04,772
- We can open
a bird museum soon.

108
00:17:04,980 --> 00:17:08,529
- You’re funny hunters.
Did you have a good time?

109
00:17:08,740 --> 00:17:10,970
He scolds me for it.

110
00:17:11,180 --> 00:17:15,412
- You lead a comfortable life.
You do as you please.

111
00:17:15,620 --> 00:17:18,976
- But with Milan.
- He isn’t difficult to live with.

112
00:17:19,180 --> 00:17:23,378
- For a foreigner, he has settled down well.
- That’s what you said.

113
00:17:25,020 --> 00:17:29,013
How are things
with your husband?

114
00:17:29,220 --> 00:17:33,532
- We don't have the time
to bother one other.

115
00:17:33,740 --> 00:17:35,219
Does he chase girls?

116
00:17:36,220 --> 00:17:39,690
- He needs a young one
from time to time.

117
00:17:40,620 --> 00:17:42,770
How do you feel about it?

118
00:17:43,660 --> 00:17:47,778
- When he's caught,
he's nicer to me.

119
00:17:47,980 --> 00:17:50,130
Say, you’re clever.

120
00:19:00,940 --> 00:19:01,895
Are you coming?

121
00:19:13,500 --> 00:19:16,412
Radiguette will never
take us seriously.

122
00:19:16,620 --> 00:19:18,531
She knows all about life.

123
00:19:18,740 --> 00:19:19,855
So do I.

124
00:19:20,060 --> 00:19:21,379
Perhaps.

125
00:19:23,820 --> 00:19:24,855
Where were you?

126
00:19:25,060 --> 00:19:28,939
- Le Mans, in '56.
The first time I drove for Jaguar.

127
00:19:29,140 --> 00:19:31,813
- You say it
as if you were scared?

128
00:19:32,020 --> 00:19:37,174
- It’s hard to find the right
word for the feeling.

129
00:19:37,380 --> 00:19:40,417
Especially at the start
of the race.

130
00:19:40,620 --> 00:19:43,532
Yet, you broke
the record that day.

131
00:19:43,740 --> 00:19:49,337
- It’s funny,
I can’t remember it very well.

132
00:19:50,540 --> 00:19:53,452
All I can remember is
the dress you were wearing.

133
00:19:53,660 --> 00:19:58,780
A blue spot, on the left,
as I approached the straightaway.

134
00:20:01,460 --> 00:20:04,930
The one you bought for me in Rome.

135
00:20:05,140 --> 00:20:06,129
Yes.

136
00:20:06,940 --> 00:20:11,855
- And while I tried it on, you made
a date with the salesgirl.

137
00:20:12,060 --> 00:20:14,620
One of life's little pleasures.

138
00:20:20,220 --> 00:20:24,008
- Aren't you getting a little
fed up with this small village?

139
00:20:26,100 --> 00:20:27,738
Here or elsewhere...

140
00:21:26,580 --> 00:21:29,458
- Don't mind me.
- Good evening, Madame Milan.

141
00:21:29,900 --> 00:21:31,811
Hello everyone!

142
00:21:33,020 --> 00:21:35,693
- How are you?
- I’m bored. It’s unbelievable.

143
00:21:37,980 --> 00:21:41,416
- It’s not funny.
- It’s the way you said it.

144
00:21:41,620 --> 00:21:42,848
Where is Mr. Milan?

145
00:21:43,060 --> 00:21:45,369
- He’s working.
- He isn't bored?

146
00:21:45,580 --> 00:21:47,855
- You'd like if he
came for you.

147
00:21:52,940 --> 00:21:53,816
Who's that?

148
00:21:54,020 --> 00:21:56,295
That's the new teacher.

149
00:22:01,820 --> 00:22:02,969
Good evening.

150
00:22:03,220 --> 00:22:04,733
Good evening, Madame.

151
00:22:06,380 --> 00:22:10,692
- Well, just in town and you're already
at the pub. We'll be great friends.

152
00:22:10,900 --> 00:22:11,969
I live here.

153
00:22:12,180 --> 00:22:14,489
- Do you want a drink?
- No, thanks.

154
00:22:14,700 --> 00:22:17,498
- You've got principles.
- No. I’m just not thirsty.

155
00:22:17,700 --> 00:22:21,295
- You have a pretty laugh.
Jacqueline, my pastis!

156
00:22:28,860 --> 00:22:31,499
You have a minute!
Have a seat.

157
00:22:31,940 --> 00:22:32,816
Yes

158
00:22:35,180 --> 00:22:36,852
I’m bored, you see.

159
00:22:37,060 --> 00:22:39,654
- I understand, you are used to
having strong emotions.

160
00:22:39,860 --> 00:22:41,213
You already know?

161
00:22:41,420 --> 00:22:44,139
It's the first thing Jacqueline told me.

162
00:22:44,460 --> 00:22:45,859
What did you say?

163
00:22:46,060 --> 00:22:49,530
- When a man like Milan
settles here...

164
00:22:49,740 --> 00:22:52,015
- Jacqueline!
- Sorry.

165
00:22:53,060 --> 00:22:55,528
- I already knew
who your husband was.

166
00:22:55,740 --> 00:22:58,015
Do you like racing?

167
00:22:58,220 --> 00:23:02,452
- At home, we watch it on TV
I saw you once.

168
00:23:02,660 --> 00:23:03,536
Oh yeah?

169
00:23:03,740 --> 00:23:06,573
- It was a day
when Mr. Milan had won.

170
00:23:06,780 --> 00:23:10,534
You were crying with joy.
I wish I had been in your place.

171
00:23:10,740 --> 00:23:12,651
I'd like to see you there!

172
00:23:14,300 --> 00:23:19,852
- It must be difficult to live
with a man like that. I couldn’t.

173
00:23:20,540 --> 00:23:22,212
Surely not.

174
00:23:26,100 --> 00:23:26,896
Hello.

175
00:23:27,100 --> 00:23:28,089
Good evening.

176
00:23:28,300 --> 00:23:30,530
- So champ,
already at your post?

177
00:23:30,740 --> 00:23:32,332
Our veterinarian, Miss...

178
00:23:32,540 --> 00:23:34,212
- Hйlиne Morel.
- Hello.

179
00:23:34,420 --> 00:23:36,138
The new teacher.

180
00:23:36,340 --> 00:23:37,898
Jacqueline, a Ricard.

181
00:23:38,940 --> 00:23:42,137
2 Ricards.
20 under the mark like usual?

182
00:23:42,340 --> 00:23:45,537
- No 40.
I have to get used to it

183
00:23:46,220 --> 00:23:47,369
I'll leave you to it.

184
00:23:47,580 --> 00:23:49,650
- Not going to play?
- No.

185
00:23:49,860 --> 00:23:50,815
Goodbye.

186
00:23:51,020 --> 00:23:52,373
Goodbye, Madam.

187
00:23:54,260 --> 00:23:57,809
- Say. Join us for dinner
tomorrow evening.

188
00:23:58,020 --> 00:23:58,930
Thanks.

189
00:23:59,140 --> 00:24:01,335
Milan adores young girls.

190
00:24:11,180 --> 00:24:14,729
No it was the year where Collins
wiped out at the chicane.

191
00:24:14,940 --> 00:24:16,976
Milan got there
just behind

192
00:24:17,180 --> 00:24:19,091
Monte Carlo, 2 years ago.

193
00:24:19,740 --> 00:24:21,298
Oh yeah, 2 years already.

194
00:24:21,500 --> 00:24:24,094
The next day we
had a sacred feast

195
00:24:24,300 --> 00:24:26,416
Colins wanted to beat me.

196
00:24:26,620 --> 00:24:27,973
He wanted to skin you!

197
00:24:28,180 --> 00:24:30,489
Don’t you remember?
At the bar?

198
00:24:30,700 --> 00:24:33,168
They sat next to us.

199
00:24:33,380 --> 00:24:35,610
I told you: They’re scheming.

200
00:24:35,820 --> 00:24:38,175
"They will have you in the chicane"

201
00:24:38,380 --> 00:24:40,416
No luck for him, that year.

202
00:24:40,620 --> 00:24:43,737
Behra was having trouble
with his tires.

203
00:24:43,940 --> 00:24:47,330
I passed him.
He pulled a long face.

204
00:24:47,540 --> 00:24:48,973
It was over for him.

205
00:24:49,180 --> 00:24:50,454
Were you going fast?

206
00:24:50,660 --> 00:24:53,857
- The Casino corner,
you enter it doing 120.

207
00:24:54,060 --> 00:24:57,211
No one has come out alive
at more than 180.

208
00:24:57,420 --> 00:24:59,650
Wow how could you see Behra’s face?

209
00:24:59,860 --> 00:25:04,138
- I was going 180, him 175.
Like 2 trains at the same speed

210
00:25:04,340 --> 00:25:05,534
I'm silly!

211
00:25:05,740 --> 00:25:07,253
I was at the top..

212
00:25:07,460 --> 00:25:09,894
.. of the chicane
with Luigi. He groaned.

213
00:25:10,100 --> 00:25:11,977
That Milan has no respect...

214
00:25:12,180 --> 00:25:16,571
They arrived at the bottom.
Moss entered too fast and wiped out.

215
00:25:16,780 --> 00:25:19,772
Collins caught Moss' wheel
and went out as well.

216
00:25:19,980 --> 00:25:21,732
A pole from the chicane..

217
00:25:21,940 --> 00:25:24,215
.. fell onto the road.
Milan arrives.

218
00:25:24,420 --> 00:25:27,730
Makes two controlled slides
and he passes through.

219
00:25:27,940 --> 00:25:29,532
You must have been scared.

220
00:25:31,980 --> 00:25:33,299
We’re always scared.

221
00:25:33,980 --> 00:25:35,299
What a life!

222
00:25:35,500 --> 00:25:38,890
- My father bought me
my first car when I was 18.

223
00:25:39,100 --> 00:25:40,738
I wanted to be
a race car driver..

224
00:25:40,940 --> 00:25:42,976
and I especially wanted
to be a writer.

225
00:25:43,180 --> 00:25:45,933
But writing is much harder.

226
00:25:46,140 --> 00:25:49,735
At first I wrote about racing.
It was a compromise.

227
00:25:49,940 --> 00:25:51,214
And later on I raced.

228
00:25:51,420 --> 00:25:53,490
That’s Monza, isn’t it?

229
00:25:55,660 --> 00:25:57,696
- Yes.
My first 1000 miles.

230
00:25:57,900 --> 00:26:01,449
I wasn't a driver yet.
I was reporting for a paper.

231
00:26:01,660 --> 00:26:04,379
Octave Zabo took me on
as a teammate.

232
00:26:04,580 --> 00:26:06,093
You guys look happy.

233
00:26:06,300 --> 00:26:10,054
- I got a taste for it.
It started with him.

234
00:26:10,260 --> 00:26:11,409
He was great.

235
00:26:12,180 --> 00:26:15,855
- Yes, but above all
he was my best friend.

236
00:26:16,060 --> 00:26:17,493
He died.

237
00:26:30,940 --> 00:26:33,659
Some brandy?
- Of course.

238
00:26:33,860 --> 00:26:35,851
She's already talking like you.

239
00:26:36,380 --> 00:26:37,335
How?

240
00:26:37,540 --> 00:26:38,495
Nothing.

241
00:26:44,340 --> 00:26:46,092
Is this your first assignment?

242
00:26:46,300 --> 00:26:48,860
- Yes. I finished school
at the end of May.

243
00:26:49,060 --> 00:26:51,494
You aren't bored in the village?

244
00:26:51,700 --> 00:26:54,339
- Not yet. I'm preparing
for a new exam.

245
00:26:54,540 --> 00:26:57,338
I want to be a travelling teacher.

246
00:26:58,500 --> 00:27:01,776
Why are you smiling?
Does that sound funny?

247
00:27:01,980 --> 00:27:04,050
No, but I don't quite understand.

248
00:27:04,260 --> 00:27:07,809
- It's for those who've
finished junior college.

249
00:27:08,020 --> 00:27:10,056
We have more freedom.

250
00:27:10,260 --> 00:27:14,572
A bit of home economics
and we take care of their leisure time.

251
00:27:14,780 --> 00:27:18,090
3 hours a week in each village per district.

252
00:27:18,300 --> 00:27:22,612
We'll go by car.
I'll start with a 2CV.

253
00:27:22,820 --> 00:27:25,380
It's a more enjoyable life.

254
00:27:25,580 --> 00:27:27,252
More independant as well.

255
00:27:28,060 --> 00:27:30,858
- Independence matters
a lot to you.

256
00:27:31,060 --> 00:27:33,210
It's the reason I work.

257
00:27:35,740 --> 00:27:38,459
When I was your age,..

258
00:27:38,660 --> 00:27:40,935
.. I thought the meaning of independence,..

259
